<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-24T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="662" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d662">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">312.1722 Sandino/7: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hawks</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-24T09:00:00-06:00">April 24, 1929—9
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 1:40 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>52. Referring to the Legation’s telegram of April 15, noon.<note n="26" xml:id="d662fn26">Not printed.</note> The Minister for Foreign
                            Affairs informed me last night that yesterday the Mexican Ambassador had
                            requested permission for Sandino to pass through Guatemala from Salvador
                            to Mexico; that this permission was granted and that Sandino will be
                            escorted through Guatemala, precautions being taken to prevent any
                            demonstration whatever.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Nicaragua, Honduras and Salvador.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hawks</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>